<DOC><DOCNO> AP880524-0179 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2045EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Explosion     05-24 0233</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-Explosion,0239</SECOND><HEAD>Eight Killed, Three Injured in Blast at Fish Farm</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A devastating explosion killed eight people andseriously injured three in a storage area of a fish farm east ofMoscow, the nightly news program Vremya reported Tuesday. Six ofthose killed were firemen.   The broadcast showed what appeared to have been a huge brickstorehouse reduced to rubble, and an announcer said the blast wasprobably the result of improper storage of chemicals or fuel.   An investigation was ordered into the cause of the explosion,Vremya said.   A.V. Larin, deputy chief of the Moscow region's fire preventionservice, told the news program local firefighters responded to areport at 11:15 p.m. Sunday of a fire at the warehouse inYegorievsk, a town of about 73,000 people approximately 60 mileseast of Moscow.   The report said six of those killed were firemen who arrived toput out the blaze and the other two were fishermen who werestanding nearby.   The broadcast said three people were in serious condition at alocal hospital, but gave no details.   The news announcer said Soviet Ministry of Fisheries enterprisesin the Russian republic alone were hit by fire 526 times in thepast two years with 63 people killed.   Vremya did not comment on the statistics, but the disclosuresuggested that the ministry is considered to be lax in enforcingsafety rules.</TEXT></DOC>